Mountain Versus Man

A Student from Fall 2019

11/25/2019

Introduction

For the novice climber or the decorated mountaineer, this project will uncover insights to better understand the relationship between mountain and man. The goal is to provide helpful decisions as to what peaks to choose from and the various factors that contribute to the success and fall of mountain climbers.

To explore this relationship, I will be utilizing data about climbers fatalities from, 8000ers.com,The top 125 topgraphic mountain dataset and a similiar dataset with various factors both from Kaggle.My approach is to make analysis and insights on the two datasets about mountains. I will then take a closer look at the relationship between climber fatalities and the analyzed data on mountains by joining these datasets. The goal here is to see if I can uncover new information in the data that isnt clear and use it to explain our key findings.

Thus with this approach I hope my analysis can give climbers, enthusiasts, and anyone in between a clear understanding of what peaks to climb, when to climb, etc and all the various factors to contribute to a successful summit.

What are the highest Peaks for each region?

This information is particularly useful for anyone looking to climb the highest peak for each region or the seven continents.

*Note there is a dispute as to whether Mount Blanc or Mount Elbrus is the highest peak in Europe. The answer depends on what the interpreters defintion of what a continent is and where its borders lie. The border between Asia and Europe can be defined by many as the caucaus mountains or the Kuma_Manycn depression. If the border is defined by the depression then Mount Blanc is the highest peak in Europe. If its defined otherwise then its in Asia, and this is the widely accepted as correct. Thus, Mount Elbrus is on the European continent and highest in Europe.

What is the median height for peaks per country? Finding the median height of a mountain for each country is useful for anyone wanting to climb in a particular country. The median was used here instead of the mean because the data can have some outliers and that would result in some unfair results, thus the median is used.

median_peaks <- mountains%>% group_by(Location)%>%summarise(median_Height=median(`Height..m.`))


h<- ggplot(data = median_peaks,mapping = aes(x=Location, y = median_Height, )) +geom_col(color='white', fill='hotpink') + coord_flip()

h+theme(axis.text.x = element_text(face="bold", color="Black"),
   axis.text.y = element_text( color="Black",  size=6 ))+ labs(x="Country Name", y="Median Height of Peak (m)")

The average height of a mountain on the Himalayas Range is 8084.636 meters. Peak Gangkhar Puensum is the lowest peak at 7570 meters and Mount Everest is the highest at 8848m. The average Height of the Himalayas Range is 8,084.636 meters. Performing a t.test i was able to find the point estimate of the average peak height on the Himalayas.

#Himalayas Range, 11 rows
avg_Himalayans<- mountains %>% select(Peak,Height..m.,RangeName)%>%filter(RangeName=="Himalayas")
unique(avg_Himalayans)%>%summarise(avg_Height=mean(Height..m.))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1

# getting the true height of the avg mountains on the himalayas
true_height<-avg_Himalayans%>%select(Peak, Height..m.)
true_height<-unique(true_height)


t.test(true_height$Height..m.)

The first mountains dataset for the Himalayas Range has a mean height of 8084.636. Doing A one-sample two-sided t.test will test whether the second dataset agrees with that. The p-value=1, so we fail to reject the null hypothesis because the p value is greater than 0.05

#Two sided t. test 
t.test(avg_Himalayans2$Height_m, mu=7612.033, alternative = "two.sided")
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  avg_Himalayans2$Height_m

##Distribution of Prominence The prominence of a peak is the height of the peaks summit above the lowest contour line encircling it and no higher summit. The smaller the prominence the greater the height. This shows that the major of mountains in this sample have a large prominence are thus not as high as believed.

mountains %>% ggvis(~Prominence..m.,fill :="DarkBlue") %>% layer_densities() %>% add_axis("y",title_offset = 60)

Successful and Unsuccessful Climbs

Are failed attempts proportionate to peak heights? What is the cause of failed attempts for climbers? Is it the higher the Peak the higher the number of failed attempts? Or are other factors not taken into account here such as difficulty of peak, skill of climber, etc. Lets take a look and perform a correlation analysis:

# correlation analysis
cor(summits$Failed_attempts, summits$Height_m, use = "complete")
## [1] 0.7327838

Turns out that there is a positive correlation between the number of failed attempts and peak height. As the peaks get higher so does the number of unsuccessful climbers, but there are more failed attempts for peaks less than 8,000 meters. In this sample 559 climbers failed at peaks greater than 8,000 meters versus the 413 climber less than 8,000 meters. So turns out that there is a 42.48% chance at at failure for climbing peaks less than 8000, and 57.51% for peaks greater than 8000m.

## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##       n
##   <int>
## 1   413
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##       n
##   <int>
## 1   559

I added an interactive representation to show the correlation between failed attempts and height. The analysis displays that heights under 8000 meters have less failed attempts than over 8000 meters.

Therefore since there are failed attempts for peaks greater than 8000 meters, it makes since that there would be a smaller number of ascents.Turns out that, this is the case.In the graph below fewer people have ascended to peaks greater than 8500 meters. I would also like to note that skilled climbers do not re-ascend peaks they have already completed, whereas beginners may do so to improve their skill.

I think this analysis could be improved upon if i had some more information about the skill level of climbers.

##Top 10 mountains most difficult to climb So to figure out what is a cause for failed attempted peaks other than heights, I think a could question to ask is how difficult the climb is.I determined that a mountain is difficult to climb by, the total number of failed attempts dived by the number of total climbs. The people who have failed out of the total attempts seem like a could measure for difficulty.

Turns out according to the graph below, Mountains that are the most difficult are not neccessarily the tallest. In the graph Mount Everest is the tallest mounatain in the world and also the most difficult. However, the second most difficult is Broad Peak which is less than 8250 meters and it well below K2 which is 8611 meters. So height is not the sole reason for failed attempts. Thus, there must be other factors at hand which contributes to failed attempts.

# bar graph of top 10 difficult mountains to climb from the Himalayas and Karakoram ranges.
ggplot(mtn, aes(x = reorder(mtn$Peak, mtn$Difficulty), y = mtn$Difficulty, fill = Height_m)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  coord_flip() +labs(y="Difficulty Level", x="Peak")+
  ggtitle("Top 10 difficult Mountains  ",
          subtitle = " For Himalayas and Karakoram Range")

Is the success rate dependent on height? Turns out that according to the graph below, peaks with a success rate between 75% and 100% are less than 8000 meters. Peaks that are above 8000 m are all classified as challenging and have a success rate of less than 25%.

Also, by looking at the plot and insight can be made about unclimed mountains.Based of the chart, the unclimbed peaks would be inbetween the range of easy and normal, with a success rate of 75-100%. So this analysis is particularly good for any climber who is seeking to set a record as being the first to summit any one of these unclimbed peaks, and has a good chance at doing so.

Summary

This analysis is intended to assist climbers to make a well informed judgement on what peaks will lead to successful summits based on the data provided. Backed by visual representations the emphasis of this analysis is to prevent any unforeseen events that may lead to fatalities that can be preventable. Hopefully decisions as to what peaks to choose from can be made from the analysis and visulization of this project.

Insights Turns out according to my analysis, Mountains that are the most difficult to climb are not neccessarily ,although common,the tallest.

However, with that being said,the easiest mountains to climb are normally less than 8000 meters with a success rate of 75-100%. Inversely, peaks greater than 8000 meters, which are challenging , have a 25% chance at success. So its wise not to choose Mount Everest as your first climb, but Im sure climbers are aware of that.

Also,the time of the year has an affect on the climber success rate. More climbers died in summer than in pre-moonsoon and much later in the years. It would been great if i could have had information on the cause of the death as that would make my analysis more insightful.

This analysis was limited by climber data such as , age, gender, skillset. We know that there is a bias in the data because beginners dont climb Everest as their first climb. So I would like to add the skillset of climbers to be joined to the previous data and see if there is indeed a bias as I suspect.

Next, I would like to incorporate data from climbers on the reason for the failed attempt and the cause of death as it may provide a deeper insight to where the problems lie. I believe that those missing pieces of information could explain as to why there are more deaths as the years go one , and when technology and equipment should be better.
